s and cultural studies, he offers a forceful critique of the Chinese version of globalism that privileges economic development at the expense of social justice and equality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGlobalizationzChina. 0aPopular culturezChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484470740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824844707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824844707/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK